{{Shrine | Name = {{ill|Kanumi Shrine|ja|加努弥神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | image = [[File:Kanumi-jinja02.jpg|270px|Kanumi Shrine]] | location = Ōnoma 1100-2, [[Shikami Town]], [[Ise City]], [[Mie Prefecture]], Japan<ref>[http://www.sengukan.jp/wp-content/themes/sengukan/shrine/area09.php "Shikinen Sengu Memorial Sengu-kan｜125 Shrines 5"] (Shikinen Sengu Memorial Sengu-kan, accessed May 3, 2015)</ref> | coordinates = {{coord|34|29|17.8|N|136|44|51.6|E|region:JP|display=inline,title}} | Map = Japan Mie | deity = Inayorihime-no-Mikoto (*稲依比女命*) | type = {{ill|Kōtai Jingū|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} subordinate shrine (*massha*) | Established = Before [[Enryaku]] 23 ([[804 CE]]) | Main Hall = None | festival = [[Kannamesai]] (*神嘗祭*) }}
'''{{ill|Kanumi Shrine|ja|加努弥神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' (*Kanumi Jinja*) is a subordinate shrine (*massha*) of {{ill|Kōtai Jingū|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (the Inner Shrine of the [[Ise Grand Shrine]]), located in [[Ise City]], [[Mie Prefecture]], Japan. It Ranks ninth among the sixteen subordinate shrines of the Inner Shrine.<ref>Ujiyamada City Office (1929): pp. 13–14.</ref>
== Overview == {{ill|Kanomi Shrine|ja|加努弥神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is located in Kanomi Town, Ise City, Mie Prefecture, amidst rice fields<ref name="ic">Ise Bunka-sha (2008): p.108</ref>. It is situated slightly away from the main settlement of Kanomi<ref name="ic"/>. Historically, the {{ill|Isuzu River|ja|五十鈴川|qq=draft|qq=draft}} used to flow close to the shrine grounds, and it is said that there was a boat dock nearby<ref name="gk">Gakken Publishing (2013): p.60</ref>.
The {{ill|shintai|ja|神体|1=Shintai|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is a stone, enshrined on a stone pavement<ref name="ic"/>. There is no shrine building (shaden)<ref name="gk"/>.
The enshrined deity is '''Inayorihime no Mikoto''' (稲依比女命)<ref name="ic"/><ref name="gk"/>, a daughter of {{ill|Ōtoshi-no-Kami|ja|大歳神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, revered as the guardian deity of grains<ref name="ic"/><ref name="gk"/>.
The shrine grounds cover an area of approximately 122 m²<ref name="uy">Ujiyamada City Hall (1929): p.14</ref>, making it the smallest shrine among the 125 shrines of the Ise Grand Shrine located outside the precincts of the Inner and {{ill|Toyouke Daijingu|ja|外宮|lt=Gekū|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<ref name="ic"/><ref name="ik">{{Cite web|ja|url=http://www.isekanko.jp/k-cycling/course08.html |title=Course 08 Asama Route — Visiting Shrines Along the Asama Mountains and Isuzu River |publisher=Ise City Tourism Association |accessdate=2013-11-16|archiveurl=https://megalodon.jp/2013-1116-2228-54/www.isekanko.jp/k-cycling/course08.html |archivedate=2013-11-16}}</ref>.
== History == The exact date of establishment is unknown, but it is confirmed to have existed before 804 (Enryaku 23), based on the compilation of the ''Kōtai Jingū Gishiki-chō''<ref>Ise Bunka-sha (2008): p.22</ref>. In 1871 (Meiji 4), with the establishment of the modern shrine Ranking system, despite being an auxiliary shrine of the Inner Shrine, it was classified as a village shrine under the jurisdiction of Watarai Prefecture, thus falling under dual jurisdiction from both the Ise Grand Shrine and Watarai Prefecture<ref name="st1">Sakurai (1991): p.271</ref>.
This dual jurisdiction also occurred with other auxiliary shrines, prompting the Jingū Office to consult with the Ministry of Education. As a result, 11 auxiliary shrines were removed from the Jingū's jurisdiction, but Kanomi Shrine and {{ill|Mike Shrine (Ise)|ja|御食神社 (伊勢市)|lt=Mike Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, an auxiliary shrine of the Outer Shrine, remained under dual jurisdiction as of April 1872 (Meiji 5)<ref name="st1"/>.
In December 1881 (Meiji 14), parishioners of Kanomi Shrine petitioned for the separation of the Inner Shrine's auxiliary shrine and the village shrine<ref name="st6">Sakurai (1991): p.276</ref>. The residents of Kanomi claimed that the auxiliary shrine and the village shrine, originally having different locations and deities, had been conflated since 1871, effectively placing them under the control of the Jingū, restricting local management<ref name="st6"/>. They presented documents showing that the village shrine "Hachioji Shrine" had been renamed "Kanomi Shrine" in 1870 (Meiji 3), with its deity changed to match that of Kanomi Shrine<ref name="st7">Sakurai (1991): p.277</ref>. After discussions among the Jingū, Mie Prefectural Office, and Ministry of Home Affairs, it was decided in February 1886 (Meiji 19) to separate the auxiliary shrine and the village shrine<ref name="st7"/>.
No separation movement was recorded for Mike Shrine, suggesting there were no issues regarding its dual jurisdiction<ref>Sakurai (1991): p.278</ref>.
== Access == The shrine is located along a farm road<ref name="ic"/>. There are no parking facilities nearby.
; Public Transportation * Approximately a 16-minute walk (about 1.3 km) from {{ill|Isuzugaoka Station|ja|五十鈴ケ丘駅|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on the {{ill|Sangū Line|ja|参宮線|qq=draft|qq=draft}} operated by JR Central. * From {{ill|Isuzugawa Station|ja|五十鈴川駅|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on the {{ill|Kintetsu Toba Line|ja|Toba Line|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, take the "Kanomi-Asama Route" {{ill|community bus|ja|コミュニティバス|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Okage Bus), get off at "Higashi Kanomi" bus stop, and walk about 3 minutes (approx. 270 m), or get off at "Nishi Kanomi" bus stop and walk about 3 minutes (approx. 320 m).
; By Car * About 2 minutes (approx. 820 m) heading east from the "Kanomi Town" intersection on National Route 23. * Approximately 4 minutes (about 1.5 km) from {{ill|Asama Interchange|ja|朝熊インターチェンジ|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on the {{ill|Ise Futami Toba Toll Road|ja|伊勢二見鳥羽有料道路|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. == References == {{Reflist|2}}
